			"id": "968f562d-8944-4d61-8189-8c5b1b908cd3",
			"note": "Some Theoretical Questions:<div><br></div><div>&nbsp;- Given a system of equations, is there a nice way to classify what the solutions look like? &nbsp; (E.g., no solutions, infinitely many, what does a picture of the set of all solutions look like?)</div><div>&nbsp;- Given a random system of $n$ equations in $m$ unknowns, what should you expect the solutions to look like? &nbsp;(The answer depends on the relation between $n$ and $m$.)</div><div>&nbsp;&nbsp;</div>"
		},
		{
			"id": "ed36dccd-dd48-4387-8276-e133b40084af",
			"note": "<div>Matrices: an incredibly useful tool for thinking about all of the above questions.</div><div><br></div><div>A matrix is a rectangular array of numbers:</div><div><br></div><div>$\\left(\\begin{matrix} 3 &amp; 3 \\\\ 4 &amp; -3\\end{matrix}\\right)$</div><div><br></div><div>Matrices can (often) be added and multiplied, assuming the number of rows and columns are compatible. &nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>Addition: add the entries component-wise (the number of rows and columns must be the same)</div><div><br></div><div>Multiplication: more complicated, but designed so that we get a way to think of a system of linear equations as a SINGLE equation involving matrices.</div>"
		},
