		{
			"id": "5fe3054d-50b7-46c6-b7f9-119696272bb8",
			"note": "<div>You solve problems in algebra by doing transformations to the equation that don't change the set of solutions. &nbsp; How does this work in linear algebra?</div><div><br></div><div>Observe that the following do not change the set of solutions of a linear system:</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;- rescale an equation &nbsp; -- no surprise, just like in elementary algebra</div><div>&nbsp;- swap equations &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; -- duh, order is irrelevant</div><div>&nbsp;- add one equation to another &nbsp;-- this requires convincing! &nbsp;all the solutions before are still solutions after, and you can go in both directions!</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>In terms of matrices, these correspond to:</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp;- rescale a row</div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp;- swap two rows</div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp;- add a row to another</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>THE IDEA -- one can apply the above operations to transform any matrix into a unique form called \"reduced row echelon form\", from which all questions about the set of solutions to a system of linear equations can be easily answered. &nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div>"
		},
